org.openimaj.video

Class Video<T extends Image<?,T>>

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.openimaj.video.Video<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - the image type of the frames
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Closeable, AutoCloseable, Iterable<T>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    AnimatedVideo, ArrayBackedVideo, FileBackedVideo, VideoProcessor, VideoTranslator

    public abstract class Video<T extends Image<?,T>>
extends Object
implements Iterable<T>, Closeable
    Abstract base class for videos.
    Author:
    Sina Samangooei (ss@ecs.soton.ac.uk), Jonathon Hare (jsh2@ecs.soton.ac.uk), David Dupplaw (dpd@ecs.soton.ac.uk)

      • setCurrentFrameIndex

        public void setCurrentFrameIndex(long newFrame)
        Set the current frame index (i.e. skips to a certain frame). If your video subclass can implement this in a cleverer way, then override this method, otherwise this method will simply grab frames until it gets to the given frame index. This method is naive and may take some time as each frame will be decoded by the video decoder.
        Parameters:
        newFrame - the new index

      • seek

        public void seek(double timestamp)
        Seek the video to a given timestamp in SECONDS. Many videos (including cameras etc.) will have no ability to seek so by default this function does nothing.

        public abstract long countFrames()
        Return the number of frames in the whole video. If the video is a live stream, then this method should return -1.

        the number of frames in the whole video or -1 if unknown
